'''Jordan Jacob Bos''' (born 29 October 2002) is an Australian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|left back]] for [[Dutch Eredivisie]] side [[Feyenoord|Feyenoord]] and the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]].

==Early life==
Bos grew up in the Melbourne suburb of [[Point Cook, Victoria|Point Cook]] and played junior football for [[Hoppers Crossing SC]]. He went to secondary school at the Point Cook campus of [[Emmanuel College, Melbourne|Emmanuel College]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roy |first1=Shilarze Saha |title=Jordan Bos: The marauding Australian left-back set to conquer Europe with Westerlo |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/jordan-bos-the-marauding-australian-left-back-set-to-conquer-europe-with-westerlo |website=FIFA |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=13 June 2023}}</ref> He is of Dutch descent,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefootballsack.com.au/2022/12/enjoy-him-while-you-can-because-jordan-bos-could-be-off-our-shores-sooner-rather-than-later.html|title=Enjoy him while you can, because Jordan Bos could be off our shores sooner rather than later|first=Caydn|last=Foley|date=28 December 2022|access-date=31 March 2023|archive-date=15 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115001918/https://thefootballsack.com.au/2022/12/enjoy-him-while-you-can-because-jordan-bos-could-be-off-our-shores-sooner-rather-than-later.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and is the older brother of [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] player [[Kasey Bos]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pisani |first1=Sacha |title=My brother is already a Socceroo & I'm ready to follow his footsteps in the A-Leagues |date=10 May 2024 |url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/a-league-semi-final-melbourne-victory-kasey-bos-tickets-broadcast-socceroos/ |publisher=A-Leagues |access-date=23 December 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Joseph |title=Bos Moves: Kasey Bos looking to seize opportunities at Victory |url=https://www.jdlmedia.com.au/p/bos-moves-kasey-bos-looking-to-seize |publisher=JDL Media |access-date=23 December 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Melbourne City===
In September 2021, Bos signed his first professional contract with [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Re-signed: Jordan Bos extends contract |url=https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/re-signed-jordan-bos-extends-contract |publisher=[[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=30 September 2021 |archive-date=29 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230329155246/https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/re-signed-jordan-bos-extends-contract |url-status=live }}</ref> Bos made his first-team debut for City on 27 November 2021 as a substitute in a 2–2 draw to [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]] at [[Hindmarsh Stadium|Coopers Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Bos (Defender, Melbourne City): 2021–22 season |url=https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1462&season=2021-22 |website=Ultimate A-League |access-date=17 October 2023 |language=en |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115001943/https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1462&season=2021-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on 6 April 2022, opening the score in a 4–0 win over [[Sydney FC]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Match Report: City 4-0 Sydney |url=https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/match-report-city-4-0-sydney |publisher=Melbourne City |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=6 April 2022 |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115001919/https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/match-report-city-4-0-sydney |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Bos (Defender, Melbourne City): 2022–23 season |url=https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1462&season=2021-22 |website=Ultimate A-League |access-date=17 October 2023 |language=en |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115001943/https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1462&season=2021-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bos was a part of Melbourne City's campaign in the [[2021–22 A-League Men|2021–22 season]] and [[2022–23 A-League Men|2022–23 season]], where he claimed two [[A-League Men]]’s Premierships in 50 appearances, including three goals and six assists, for the club.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |title=Australian record transfer sees Jordan Bos move to Belgian Pro League |url=https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/australian-record-transfer-sees-jordan-bos-move-to-belgian-pro-league |publisher=Melbourne City |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=15 May 2023 |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002023/https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/australian-record-transfer-sees-jordan-bos-move-to-belgian-pro-league |url-status=live }}</ref>

===KVC Westerlo===
On 16 May 2023, it was announced that Bos would join [[Belgian Pro League]] side [[KVC Westerlo|Westerlo]] at the end of the 2022–23 season, signing a four-year contract with his new club.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Herck |first=Glen Van |date=16 May 2023 |title=Welkom Jordan! |url=https://kvcwesterlo.be/2023/05/15/welkom-jordan/ |access-date=20 May 2023 |website=KVC Westerlo |language=nl-BE |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002025/https://kvcwesterlo.be/2023/05/15/welkom-jordan/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=16 May 2023 |title=Jordan Bos breaks A-League Men transfer record with move to Belgian club |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/may/16/jordan-bos-breaks-a-league-men-transfer-record-with-move-to-belgian-club |access-date=20 May 2023 |website=The Guardian |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002733/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/may/16/jordan-bos-breaks-a-league-men-transfer-record-with-move-to-belgian-club |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Joshua |title=Record-breaking Jordan Bos transfer a 'fantastic deal' for everyone as pay cheque 'advice' seals Belgium move |url=https://sport.optus.com.au/news/australian-football/os57778/jordan-bos-tranfer-westerlo-melbourne-city-socceroos |website=Optus Sport |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=17 May 2023 |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002723/https://sport.optus.com.au/news/australian-football/os57778/jordan-bos-tranfer-westerlo-melbourne-city-socceroos |url-status=live }}</ref> While the transfer fee was kept undisclosed, it was reported that the deal broke the previous records both for Melbourne City (originally set by [[Aaron Mooy]] in 2016) and for any [[A-League Men|A-League]] club (which had belonged to [[Zeljko Kalac]] since 1995).<ref name=":1"/><ref name=":0"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Joey |title=Bos move: City star sets A-League transfer record |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/37674906/melbourne-city-jordan-bos-sets-australian-transfer-record |website=ESPN |access-date=17 October 2023 |language=en |date=15 May 2023 |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002657/https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/37674906/melbourne-city-jordan-bos-sets-australian-transfer-record |url-status=live }}</ref> Bos' record as the most expensive transfer domestic player in Australia stood until June 2023, when former teammate [[Marco Tilio]] was sold to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] from City for a record undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marco Tilio joins Celtic FC in record-breaking transfer |url=https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/20230630-marco-tilio-departs |publisher=Melbourne City |access-date=17 October 2023 |date=30 June 2023 |archive-date=15 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002730/https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/20230630-marco-tilio-departs |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Feyenoord===
On 25 July 2025, Bos moved to Dutch side [[Feyenoord]] on a four year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/feyenoord-haalt-australische-concurrent-voor-gijs-smal |title=Feyenoord haalt Australische concurrent voor Gijs Smal |trans-title=Feyenoord brings in Australian competitor for Gijs Smal |language=Dutch |date=25 July 2025 |access-date=25 July 2025}}</ref>

He made his first competitive start against [[Galatasaray]] in a UEFA Champions League Qualifier, assisting a 91st minute winner from [[Anis Hadj Moussa]]. Bos’ first goal for the club came on 31 August, being the opener in a 4–0 away win vs [[Sparta Rotterdam]]. His good form continued, as he scored from outside the box against [[AZ Alkmaar]] in a 3–3 draw on 21 September. This run would constitute his best start to a season, with 4 goal involvements in his first 6 games. He was later  named the [[Eredivisie Player of the Month]] for the month of September,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eredivisie.eu/news/jordan-bos-named-player-of-the-month-for-september/ |title=Jordan Bos named Player of the Month for September |language=English |date=4 October 2025}}</ref> becoming the first Australian to win the award.

==International career==
[[File:4822274 AE7I6730 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|251x251px|Bos with [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] at the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]]]]
Bos made his international debut for [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] in a friendly against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] at [[Docklands Stadium]] on 28 March 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/bos-fulfils-childhood-dream-after-socceroos-debut|title=Bos fulfils childhood dream after Socceroos debut|date=5 April 2023|access-date=16 May 2023|archive-date=3 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230703031626/https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/bos-fulfils-childhood-dream-after-socceroos-debut|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal against [[India men's national football team|India]] in their 2–0 win at the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]] on 13 January 2024.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australia swat aside India to launch Asian Cup title bid|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/australia-swat-aside-india-to-launch-asian-cup-title-bid/article67738073.ece|date=13 January 2024|access-date=13 January 2024|website=thehindu.com|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|agency=AFP|archive-date=15 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240115002622/https://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/australia-swat-aside-india-to-launch-asian-cup-title-bid/article67738073.ece|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the second round of [[2026_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_(AFC)#Third_round|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]], Bos assisted in each of Australia's matches against [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]].

After injuring his hamstring playing domestically, Bos missed two matches in Australia's 2026 FIFA World Cup qualification, sitting on the sidelines for matches against [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] and [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] in September of 2024. He returned for a 3–1 victory over [[China national football team|China]] in October.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ajdin Hrustic and Jordan Bos edging towards returning for the Socceroos|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/breaking-news/ajdin-hrustic-and-jordan-bos-edging-towards-returning-for-the-socceroos/news-story/0ea3c4ba5b6fbcc1ba04caef9974bebb|first=Marco|last=Monteverde|date=16 September 2024|publisher=[[The Australian]]|website=theaustralian.com.au}}</ref>
